SIMPLE: tripod
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tripod
<hw>Tri"pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tripus</ets>,
<ets>-odis</ets>, Gr. <?/; <?/ (see <er>Tri-</er>) + <?/, <?/, foot. See
<er>Foot</er>, and cf. <er>Tripos</er>, <er>Trivet</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Any utensil or vessel, as a stool, table, altar,
caldron, etc., supported on three feet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ On such, a stool, in the temple of Apollo at Delphi, the
Pythian priestess sat while giving responses to those consulting the
Delphic oracle.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A three-legged frame or stand, usually jointed at
top, for supporting a theodolite, compass, telescope, camera, or other
instrument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Tripod of life</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Vital
tripod</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>the three organs, the
heart, lungs, and brain; -- so called because their united action is
necessary to the maintenance of life.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tripodian</ent>⟦br⟧
